main event: A ground-visual observation was reported in Nekoosa, Wisconsin on 16th November 1956. The observation lasted for one minute and involved a single stationary object, believed to be a meteor by the reporting officer.
interesting points: The observation was of a single white light, with a tail as long as the object, which gradually faded out.
The observation was consistent with a bright flash of light at a 38 degree angle, descending to 333 degrees, and fading out after one minute.
The witness, a supermarket supervisor, reported a clear sighting of a possible meteorite.
The report mentions the involvement of the USAF in analyzing the sighting.
Despite the initial impression of a UFO, the reporting officer suggested a prozaic explanation of the observed object being a meteor.
sighted object: single stationary white light, potentially a meteor
